---
name: scljet-write-keyed
description: SclJet M3 explicit-rowid table writer — rows keep their own (gapped) rowids across a rewrite, cross-backend
backends: [int, js]
---

# SclJet explicit-rowid writer

[ByteSlice, byteSliceToList, SqliteValue, SqlInteger, SqlText, KeyedRow, buildKeyedDatabase](std/scljet/index.ssc)

```scalascript
def text(n: Int): String =
  if n <= 0 then ""
  else if n == 1 then "a"
  else
    val half = text(n / 2)
    if n % 2 == 0 then half + half else half + half + "a"

// Explicit, non-contiguous rowids (10, 25, 100, 500, 1000) — the shape left after
// deleting rows from a table — are preserved verbatim rather than renumbered
// 1..n. Row 100 carries a 1016-char value that spills onto an overflow chain, so
// the keyed writer composes with overflow. Reference integrity_check accepts the
// file and every (rowid, value) reads back exact.
val rows = List(
  KeyedRow(10L, List(SqlInteger(10L), SqlText("ten"))),
  KeyedRow(25L, List(SqlInteger(25L), SqlText("twentyfive"))),
  KeyedRow(100L, List(SqlInteger(100L), SqlText(text(1016)))),
  KeyedRow(500L, List(SqlInteger(500L), SqlText("fivehundred"))),
  KeyedRow(1000L, List(SqlInteger(1000L), SqlText("thousand"))))

buildKeyedDatabase(512, 7, 3, "t", "CREATE TABLE t(n INTEGER, v TEXT)", rows) match
  case Right(bytes) => println((bytes.length / 512).toString + ":" + byteSliceToList(bytes).toString)
  case Left(error) => println("ERROR:" + error.message)
```
